  "text": "## Graceful Shutdown Signal Handling Across Go Services\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\n**Signal Handler Registration:**\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal.go` defines `SetupSignalContext()` and `SetupSignalHandler()` functions\n- Uses `signal.Notify(shutdownHandler, shutdownSignals...)` to register for SIGTERM and SIGINT\n- Creates a buffered channel (size 2) to handle multiple signals: the first signal triggers shutdown via context cancellation, the second signal forces exit with code 1\n- Line 46: `signal.Notify(shutdownHandler, shutdownSignals...)`\n- Line 48-51: On first signal, cancel context; on second signal, exit immediately\n\n**Shutdown Timeout:**\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/genericapiserver.go` defines multiple timeout values:\n  - `ShutdownDelayDuration`: Default 70 seconds - delay before initiating HTTP server shutdown (allows readiness probes to fail)\n  - `ShutdownTimeout`: Default 60 seconds - timeout for HTTP server graceful shutdown (line 585-595)\n  - When `ShutdownSendRetryAfter` is true, shutdown timeout is reduced to 2 seconds\n\n**Cleanup Ordering (Drain Before Stop Goroutines):**\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/lifecycle_signals.go` documents the detailed shutdown sequence with multiple lifecycle events:\n  1. ShutdownInitiated (KILL signal received)\n  2. AfterShutdownDelayDuration (70s elapsed, readiness fails)\n  3. PreShutdownHooksStopped (pre-shutdown hooks complete)\n  4. NotAcceptingNewRequest (stop accepting new requests)\n  5. InFlightRequestsDrained (existing requests complete, up to 60s timeout)\n  6. HTTPServerStoppedListening (HTTP server stops accepting connections)\n\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/genericapiserver.go` lines 580-650 show the orchestration:\n  - Wait for shutdown delay (line 581)\n  - Drain in-flight requests BEFORE calling server.Shutdown() (line 622)\n  - AuditBackend.Run() waits for drained channel before shutdown (line 617)\n  - Line 622: `stoppedCh, listenerStoppedCh, err := s.NonBlockingRunWithContext(stopHTTPServerCtx, shutdownTimeout)`\n\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/secure_serving.go` lines 231-242:\n  - Waits for stopCh signal\n  - Creates context with timeout (line 236): `ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), shutDownTimeout)`\n  - Calls server.Shutdown(ctx) with deadline (line 238)\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\n\n**Signal Handler Registration:**\n- `cmd/prometheus/main.go` lines 1154-1155:\n  - `term := make(chan os.Signal, 1)`\n  - `signal.Notify(term, os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)`\n- SIGHUP handler at line 1266 for configuration reload\n\n**Shutdown Mechanism Using oklog/run.Group:**\n- Lines 1151-1540: Uses `github.com/oklog/run.Group` pattern for structured goroutine management\n- Each component (TSDB, web handler, notifier, etc.) is added to the group with an Execute function and interrupt handler\n- The group coordinates shutdown: when one component stops, its interrupt handler is called\n- Line 1536: `if err := g.Run(); err != nil { ... }` runs all goroutines until first error\n- Termination handler (lines 1153-1176): closes a channel on signal reception, which triggers interrupt handlers\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\n- The oklog/run.Group ensures structured shutdown ordering\n- Web handler's interrupt (line 1173): `webHandler.SetReady(web.Stopping)` sets server state\n- Notifier manager's interrupt (line 1530-1531): calls `notifierManager.Stop()` to drain queues\n- Each component's interrupt function handles graceful cleanup before TSDB and other managers shut down\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\n\n**Signal Handler Registration:**\n- Multiple operators register SIGINT/SIGTERM handlers:\n  - `pkg/operators/provisioning/connection_operator.go` line 36-37:\n    - `sigChan := make(chan os.Signal, 1)`\n    - `signal.Notify(sigChan, syscall.SIGINT, syscall.SIGTERM)`\n  - Similar pattern in `repo_operator.go` (line 39-40), `zanzana_folder_reconciler.go` (line 48-49), `jobs_operator.go` (line 57-58)\n  - All signal handlers cancel a context to stop controller loops\n\n**Shutdown Timeout:**\n- `pkg/services/grpcserver/service.go` lines 183-199:\n  - `shutdown()` function initiates graceful stop (line 188): `s.server.GracefulStop()`\n  - Timeout mechanism at lines 192-198:\n    - `select { case <-gracefulStopDone: ... case <-time.After(s.cfg.GracefulShutdownTimeout): ... }`\n    - If timeout exceeded, forces stop with `s.server.Stop()`\n\n**Cleanup Ordering:**\n- `pkg/server/module_server.go` lines 326-346 - `Shutdown()` function:\n  - Line 334: `s.shutdownFn()` cancels root context to stop all background services\n  - Lines 336-342: Wait for shutdown with context timeout\n  - If shutdown doesn't complete before timeout, returns timeout error\n- Operators use context cancellation propagation: when signal is received (line 39-41), cancel context which stops controller.Run()\n\n## Common Patterns\n\nAll three services follow these graceful shutdown principles:\n1. **Signal handler registration**: Register SIGTERM/SIGINT before starting main work\n2. **Context-based cancellation**: Use context.WithCancel() to propagate shutdown signals\n3. **Timeout protection**: Always have timeouts to prevent hanging processes\n4. **Drain before stop**: Complete in-flight work before stopping goroutines:\n   - Kubernetes: explicitly waits for InFlightRequestsDrained lifecycle event\n   - Prometheus: oklog/run.Group coordinates component shutdown order\n   - Grafana: context cancellation propagates to all background services before returning\n"
}

